snippet.textDisplay:
I'm just gonna go ahead and write something sappy real quick before it's too late and I forget what I was trying to write in the first place.
When Worlds first came out in 2014, it felt like a lifetime ago for me. I was still in high school, about to graduate and go off to college. I was so full of hope and optimism about my future, and Worlds reflected on that sentiment... the promise of a place out there that existed for the sole purpose of creativity. A fictional utopia of sorts, where depression and insecurity clouded the surface but never quite penetrated the impassable barrier that was limitless freedom of expression.
Then a few years went by. My depression got worse, and my desire to be an artist was crippled by criticism among negative reception of my work, tragic family setbacks, toxic environments/communities and people who literally went out of their way to tell me that I wasn't welcome among them. These things and more lead me to sink into a deep, emotional funk where I felt that I could no longer do the same things I used to- and in fact, I became scared of creating. Scared of picking up a pencil and drawing, or editing a video, or doing anything to give something of myself to the rest of the world. I felt in a similar way that Porter did around the same period of time- My entire life resolved around art and creating, but for the first time in my life, I was struggling to create even the simplest things. I felt that the more I tried, the more I just didn't feel like I was any good at anything. And the more people expected out of me, the more I felt forced to confront myself and tell myself that I wasn't good enough for them, and myself.
In recent months, my life has picked up a little bit. I got a steady job recently, saw a really good therapist for a while, and I've been reconnecting with the small network of friends who stood by me all those years when I was at my lowest. I felt like I was not entirely recovered, but getting there, and considered even for a little bit to start creating again.
This song, Get your Wish, came out at the exact time I needed it to. When the point in my life was so overcrowded with remorse for the past, but hope for the future. Porter has crafted, in essence, a breakdown of the last couple years of my life with this song and perhaps with the rest of the album in question.
And for that... I thank you, Porter. Thank you, even if it was just for 3 minutes and 37 seconds, for helping me find a reason to keep going.
Did I get my wish after all?

Not sure. But I guess there's still time for that.
"We'll see creation come undone /These bones that bound us will be gone/We'll stir our spirits 'til we're one/ Then softest shadows will be gone."

snippet.textDisplay:
Played this the other evening.

After seeing friends I haven’t seen for 6 years, wondered through the streets of Shibuya at 1am, on my way home. Listening to this soothing music, walking through a city that is normally crowded but late at night is a strangely peaceful scene. Seeing all the neon lights and skyscrapers, but also the ordinary houses and streets.

Seeing this made me think, I’ve had a lot of ordinary and extraordinary experiences. What do I value most in life, who means something to me, am I doing something with my life that makes me look back and smile. Some of my friends are getting married, some are CEOs , some are barely making ends meet, some are even dead. But what am I doing that derives some kind of value.

I moved to Tokyo one year ago with no plan for the future. I’ve managed to crawl out of unemployment and homelessness into a nice job. However, there’s something still empty.

I’m not sure how it feels to walk on water since that’s what I’m doing. I should be sinking but I’m somehow making it here: floating to the surface.

Right now it’s no longer evening, but it’s daytime. Walking through the crowded Tokyo station, everyone wearing the same suit as me. I may look the same as them but inside I’m very different.

Did I get my wish?

What is my wish?

Thank you Porter
